title: Police data collection request (2016-2017) (Vermont State Police)

communications.subject: Vermont Public Records Act Request: Police data collection request (2016-2017) (Vermont State Police)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Vermont Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. the total number of use of force incidents, separated by year from 2016-2017 (for example, "52 use of force incidents in 2016, 48 use of force incidents in 2017, etc.)
2. the total number of use of force incidents, separated by year and by type of force used from 2016-2017 (for example, "27 taser incidents in 2016, 3 baton incidents in 2017, etc.)

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Samuel Sinyangwe

title: FOIA Request for Body Cam Footage Related to the Death of Daunte Wright

communications.subject: Minnesota Government Data Practices Act Request: FOIA Request for Body Cam Footage Related to the Death of Daunte Wright
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Minnesota Government Data Practices Act, I hereby request the following records:

Here's an updated version of the FOIA request, specifically focused on obtaining body cam footage:

FOIA Request for Body Cam Footage Related to the Death of Daunte Wright

Date: September 17, 2024

To:
Hennepin County Sheriff’s Office
Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Officer
350 South Fifth Street, Room 6
Minneapolis, MN 55415

Subject: Freedom of Information Act Request – Body Cam Footage in Daunte Wright Case

Dear FOIA Officer,

Pursuant to the Minnesota Government Data Practices Act (MGDPA) and other applicable statutes or regulations, I am requesting access to body cam footage and any related records associated with the incident involving former Brooklyn Center police officer Kimberly Potter and Daunte Wright, which occurred on April 11, 2021.

Specifically, I am requesting the following:

All body cam footage recorded by Officer Kimberly Potter and any other officers present at the scene during the traffic stop and subsequent shooting of Daunte Wright.

Any accompanying audio or video footage from police vehicles (dash cams), or other law enforcement equipment during this incident.

Documents or reports detailing the chain of custody, storage, and preservation of the body cam footage related to this incident.

Any transcripts or logs related to the review or use of the body cam footage in the investigation or trial preparation for this case.

If possible, I would prefer to receive these records electronically at [Your Email Address]. If there are any fees associated with this request, please inform me in advance.

I look forward to your response within the timeframe required by law. If this request should be directed to another agency or department, please let me know.

Thank you for your time and assistance in processing this request.

Sincerely,

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Greg Robinson

communications.subject: RE: Minnesota Government Data Practices Act Request: FOIA Request for Body Cam Footage Related to the Death of Daunte Wright
communications.communication:
Dear FOIA Officer,

I hope this message finds you well. I am writing to follow up on my Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request, submitted on September 17, 2024, seeking the following records related to the death of Daunte Wright:

All body cam footage recorded by Officer Kimberly Potter and any other officers present at the scene during the traffic stop and subsequent shooting.
Any accompanying audio or video footage from police vehicles (dash cams) or other law enforcement equipment during the incident.
Documents or reports detailing the chain of custody, storage, and preservation of the body cam footage.
Any transcripts or logs related to the review or use of the body cam footage.
I understand that fulfilling such requests can take time, but I would appreciate any updates you can provide regarding the status of my request. Additionally, please let me know if there are any issues or fees associated with processing my request.

I would prefer to receive the requested materials electronically, if possible, at dgrobinson81@gmail.com.

Thank you for your time and assistance. I look forward to your response.

Best regards,

dgrobinson81@gmail.com

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Pierce County police disciplinary files
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States.
- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Dillon Bergin

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Third Party Investigative Platform (Purchase and Contract records) (Vancouver Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the records listed below regarding the following four software programs: 

• Thompson Reuters Clear (https://legal.thomsonreuters.com/en/products/clear)
• LexisNexis Accurint (https://www.accurint.com/)
• TransUnion TLOxp, which may also be part of the TruLookup system (https://www.tlo.com/law-enforcement)
• SoundThinking CrimeTracer, which was formerly a product called COPLINK X (https://www.soundthinking.com/law-enforcement/crime-analysis-crimetracer/) from the company formerly known as ShotSpotter

For each of the above mentioned platforms, please provide the following records: 

• CONTRACTS AND AGREEMENTS —  All contracts (as well as associated amendments, attachments, and exhibits) and agreements related to the acquisition and use of these "software" programs.
• PURCHASE INFORMATION — All invoices and purchase information for costs and products associated with the above-referenced platforms.

Please provide responsive materials for the period from January 1, 2021 through the date this request is processed. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Beryl Lipton

title: North Carolina Public Records Law Request: Fire Inspectors Report from Greene County Court Fire February 20, 2015

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: North Carolina Public Records Law Request: Fire Inspectors Report from Greene County Court Fire February 20, 2015
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the North Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

A. From the Feb 20, 2015 at 12:01 AM Feb 20, 2015 at 7:17 PM Investigation SNOW HILL, Greene County Courthouse fire led to staff evacuating the building before court convened in the matters of ex-parte 14CVD305 civil and criminal 14CRS50523 Judge Timothy Ivan Finan presiding. We request:

1. Provide copy of the onsite Snow Hill Fire Inspector's Investigative Initial Report, detail findings, and
2. Provide "any and all" hand written notes taken by inspector and\or those acting on behalf of inspector onsite at time fire;
3. Provide "any and all" inspectors or those acting on behalf taking "interior photos taken" of the clerk of the court main office; and
4. Provide "any and all" inspectors or those acting on behalf taken photos of the adjacent office "RECORDS ROOM"
5. Provide "any and all" inspectors or others acting on behalf taken photos of the "suspected' Underwriters Labs (UL) space heater alleged to be cause of the February 20, 2015 fire;
6. Provide "any and all" other 'INTERIOR PHOTOS' associated with the February 20, 2015 Greene County Clerk office fire; and
7. Provided "any and all' "inspectors and ATF" to and from emails from February 20, 2015 to December 8, 2020 and
8. Provide the Inspectors "FINAL FIRE REPORT" and FINAL INSURANCE INSPECTOR REPORT
//END

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter.

I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

SADAN NEWS

title: Request for Body Cam Footage of Incident on July 20, 2023

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Request for Body Cam Footage of Incident on July 20, 2023
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

Incident Details for Footage Retrieval:

Date: July 20, 2023
Location: 7000 block of East Drive, North Bay Village, FL
Suspect: Crystal Alisha Brewster, 33
Incident Summary: Brewster was arrested for allegedly defrauding a taxi driver and committing battery on a person aged 65 or older. The incident occurred after she failed to pay the full fare for a taxi ride, engaged in a physical altercation with the driver, and was later identified and detained by police. Surveillance footage reportedly confirmed the victim’s account, and an officer from North Miami Police assisted in translating for the victim.
I am requesting copies of all body-worn camera footage from officers who:

Responded to the initial call.
Participated in detaining or arresting Brewster.
Conducted any interviews with Brewster or the victim.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Harun

title: Wisconsin SEA response

communications.subject: Wisconsin Open Records Act Request: Wisconsin SEA response
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Wisconsin Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All documentation submitted to the U.S. Department of Education's Student Privacy Policy Office in response to the office's March 28, 2025, request for records such as "'reports, information on policies and procedures, annual notifications, training materials or other information necessary' to provide assurance that the SEA and their respective LEAs are complying with the provisions of FERPA and PPRA".

I have attached a copy of the SPPO's request letter for reference. The relevant section is found on the last page, under "Assurance of Compliance". The SPPO requested the documentation be submitted no later than April 30, 2025. If the Wisconsin Department of Public Instruction sent communications to the SPPO requesting an extension or declining to submit the documentation, I request a copy of said communications.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as I believe this request is in the public interest. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

- Full names

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

communications.subject: YOUR REQUEST HAS BEEN RECEIVED Re: Colorado Open Records Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
The Colorado Department of Corrections is a criminal justice agency and, as such, requests will be reviewed and responded to in accordance with the Colorado Criminal Justice Records Act (C.R.S. 24-72-301 et.seq.) 
Requests received by the Records Custodian after 3 pm or any day that the Department of Corrections is officially closed will be considered received as of the next business day. Responses are typically provided within 7 business days of receipt (excluding weekends, holidays). If you have not received your response within 7 business days of receipt, please re-send your request so we can provide a status update. 
If the request is for medical records; the response time is 30 days once a signed HIPAA compliant release of information consent, and any other required documentation, has been received by the medical records technician or designee at the appropriate facility. 
Please note: The Department of Corrections may charge an hourly fee for the research, retrieval and preparation of records. The first hour of research, retrieval and preparation are without charge. Beyond the first hour, the fees may vary depending on the type of record and the discretion of the custodian but will not exceed $33 per hour. You will be advised in advance if your request will incur a fee. 
In addition to the research, retrieval and production fees, there is a .25 per page fee for paper copies. The per page fee is not charged for electronic documents, however, research, retrieval and production fees still apply. Any fees due are payable in advance. Responsive documents will not be produced until payment has been tendered. 
Fees may be waived by the Department on recommendation of the records custodian.

communications.subject: [Document Released to Requester] Kentucky State Police public records request #25-4565
communications.communication:
Kentucky State Police ************************************************************************ Documents have been released for record request #25-4565 along with the following message: We are complying with your request. Our office has located the CAD and two citations. The records are attached. Certain information has been redacted from the attached record pursuant to KRS 61.878(1)(a). That statute exempts “information of a personal nature where the public disclosure thereof would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy[.]” Id. This type of information includes social security numbers, date(s) of birth, operator license number(s), personal addresses, and telephone numbers, the disclosure of which may leave persons at risk for identity theft. See Zink v. Commonwealth, 902 S.W.2d 825 (Ky. App. 1994).  The Kentucky State Police ("KSP") conducted a diligent search, but was unable to locate any other responsive records. KSP “cannot afford a requester access to a record that it does not have or that does not exist, 99-ORD-98, and the agency discharges its duty under the Open Records Act by affirmatively so stating.” 16-ORD-246 (citing 99-ORD-150). The right to inspect records, and the corollary right to receive copies, only attaches if the records requested are “prepared, owned, used, in the possession of or retained by a public agency.” KRS 61.870(2); 02-ORD-120, p. 10; 04-ORD-205. Further, a public agency is not statutorily required to “prove a negative” in order to refute an unsubstantiated claim that certain records exist. See Bowling v. Lexington-Fayette Urban County Gov’t, 172 S.W.3d 333, 341 (Ky. 2005) (“before a complaining party is entitled to such a hearing [to refute the agency’s claim that records do not exist], he or she must make a prima facie showing that such records do exist”); 11-ORD-037. KSP has confirmed that no other record exists because a search for numbers 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 and 8 within your request produced no responsive records. Accordingly, KSP has discharged its duty regarding your request by notifying you in a timely response that a diligent search did not yield any results and explaining the reason for the nonexistence of such records in the possession of KSP. See Eplion v. Burchett, 354 S.W.3d 598, 604 (Ky. App. 2011) (declaring that “when it is determined that an agency’s records do not exist, the person requesting the records is entitled to a written explanation for their nonexistence”).  If you wish to appeal this decision, you may do so by filing a complaint with the Office of the Attorney General, Open Records/Open Meetings Division, The Capitol, 700 Capital Avenue, Suite 118, Frankfort, KY 40601, pursuant to KRS 61.880(2), or by filing an original action in Franklin Circuit Court under KRS 61.882. If you first appeal to the Attorney General but are dissatisfied with the Attorney General’s decision, you may further appeal to Circuit Court pursuant to KRS 61.880(5). * citation document-redact May 27_ 2025_ 12_21_11.pdf * 10-8 Systems document-redact May 27_ 2025_ 12_17_31.pdf * citation 2 document-redact May 27_ 2025_ 12_18_18.pdf Document links are valid for one month. After July 2, you will need to sign in to view the document(s). ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at Kentucky State Police.

Technical support: See our help page

title: Evergreen Solutions (Onondaga Central School District)

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Evergreen Solutions (Onondaga Central School District)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

To Whom It May Concern:


Subject: Request for Public Records - 

Greetings,

I hope this email finds you well. We at Evergreen Solutions, LLC, are conducting a compensation study on behalf of our client and I am writing to make a formal open records request. We are requesting an electronic copy of your staff and faculty (if applicable) database as well as relevant documents such as job descriptions, collective bargaining agreements, and pay plans. I am able to send survey templates to assist with the data collection; however, we will accept data in the manner most convenient for you.

Staff Census Information requested:

Job Titles
Classification Title
Pay Grades
Pay Ranges (Minimum and Maximum)
Actual Salaries
Full-Time Equivalent (FTE) Status
Staff Handbook

I also kindly request answers to the following questions related to the compensation study:

How are salaries adjusted for your organization (e.g., COLA, Longevity, performance, etc.)?
What is your current turnover rate?
What is your current average tenure for an employee?
Date your current compensation plan was implemented.
Date of the last salary adjustment?
How frequently are job descriptions updated?

For the faculty database, I am requesting the following information:

Faculty Census:
Rank (if applicable)
Classification Title (if faculty holds other positions other than teaching such as Dean, Chair, Coordinators,etc)
Highest Degree Held
Pay Grade
Pay Ranges (Min& Max)
Current Step (if on a step plan)
Contract Length (in days and/or months)
Annual Base Salary with no additives
Annual Salary with any additives
Discipline (Not to be confused with department, the distinct/specific subject the faculty member teaches; Ex: Microbiology)
Department
CIP Code (if available - by individual incumbent)

Additionally, copies of the following documents, if available:

Copy of all faculty pay plans
Employee Benefit Information (Holidays Off, Health Insurance, Etc)
Salary Adjustment Policy (Longevity, performance, COLA, etc)
Any Collective Bargaining Agreements
Current Turnover Rate
Current Average Tenure
Date that your current pay plan was implemented
Date of your last salary adjustment to pay plan
How frequently are your job descriptions updated
Do you have a planned salary adjustment to your compensation structures for the next fiscal year? If so, by what amount?
Please list/attach and supplements/additives that faculty are compensated for duties outside of instruction
Faculty Handbooks
Adjunct Rates/Pay Plan
Overload Rates
Rates for compensation for faculty leadership- Deans, Coordinators, Department Chairs
Do you compensate faculty differently based on area of discipline? If yes, please provide details.
Do you have any form of additional compensation for Large Class Size? If yes, please provide details.
Do you have an education incentive at your institution? If yes, please provide details.

I understand that public records requests may involve administrative processes and associated fees, as allowed by law. Please inform me of any fees and the estimated timeframe for fulfilling this request. If any portion of this request is denied, please provide a written explanation for the denial, citing the specific legal grounds for the refusal.

Please consider this email as a formal request for public records under the applicable open records laws. If there are any questions or additional details needed to process this request, please do not hesitate to contact me.

I look forward to your prompt attention to this matter and the timely provision of the requested information. Your cooperation in ensuring transparency and access to public records is greatly appreciated.

Do you agree to the redaction of information that is subject to mandatory exceptions, provided such redactions are clearly labeled on information you receive?: Yes
Do you agree to the redaction of information that is subject to discretionary exceptions, provided such redactions are clearly labeled on information you receive? Yes

Email: alisia@consultevergreen.com

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Alisia Rios

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Request for Bodycam Footage – Arrest of Lakenry Roberts on 01/23/2023
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting the body-worn camera footage of the officers who arrested Lakenry B. Roberts. He was taken into custody by the Valdosta Police Department on January 23, 2023, after being found asleep behind the wheel at the intersection of West Magnolia Street and N St. Augustine Road around 2:20 AM. Upon waking him, officers observed signs of impairment and discovered Roberts had a handgun. After a brief conversation, Roberts fled the scene on foot and was apprehended shortly after. He was charged with DUI, possession of a firearm by a convicted felon, obstruction of an officer, suspended license, and open container. I am requesting the available body-worn camera footage from the responding officers who made contact with Roberts, removed the weapon, and took him into custody following the foot pursuit.

Suspect’s Name:
Lakenry B. Roberts

Type of Crime:
DUI, Possession of a Firearm by a Convicted Felon, Obstruction, Suspended License, Open Container

Date of the Arrest:
01/23/2023

Time of the Arrest:
Approximately 2:20 AM

Location of the Arrest:
Intersection of West Magnolia Street and N St. Augustine Road, Valdosta, GA


Arresting Agency: Valdosta Police Department  (booked in Lowndes County jail)

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

communications.subject: RE: California Public Records Act Request: Vinay Prasad Emails [UCSF PRA# 025-034]
communications.communication:
Dear Clinton Tyree,

This is to acknowledge UCSF receipt of your request for records under the California Public Records Act (CPRA) of March 24, 2025, PRA# 025-034, as found below:

“Any emails to or from Jay Bhattacharya from January 1, 2020 to March 25, 2025.”
However, before the University can continue to process your request, we will need some additional clarification.  In order to search for and collect “all emails to or from Jay Bhattacharya” for a period of more than four years, we will need to know first, who you would like us to contact and if you have any other clarifying keywords to include to help guide the search.  Are you requesting that we contact only Dr. Vinay Prasad, who is referenced in the subject line of your email?

Please note that in accordance with the UC Electronic Communications Policy (ECP), we are not able to search centrally for all email to or from a particular individual or with a particular keyword.  Instead, we are obligated to contact specific individuals to inquire about the existence of records that may be responsive to a given request.  You should also note that personal communications that fall outside of University business, such that they exist, would not be included.

Once we hear back from you with clarification, we can continue to process your request, PRA# 025-034.

Thank you,

PRA Team
Office of the Executive Vice Chancellor and Provost
University of California, San Francisco

You should also note that personal communications that fall outside of University business, such that they exist, would not be included.

PRA Team

According to a press release from Gov. Kemp's office on June 8, 2023, the Governor's office awarded more than $83.5 million in grants for 118 qualified projects as part of the Community Public Safety Grant program.

This included a grant of $832,960.70 awarded to Forsyth County described in additional documents provided by the Governor.

source: https://gov.georgia.gov/press-releases/2023-06-08/gov-kemp-announces-835m-community-public-safety-grant-awards

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of all documents, including but not limited to, applications, agreements, and reporting documents from the "Community Public Safety Grant" program for the grant of $832,960.70 awarded to Forsyth County as described in the Governor's press release and additional documents.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

e

title: California Police and Immigration (Santa Barbara County Sheriff's Office)

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Hello, 

I am requesting records and data related to Senate Bill 674. The law requires certifying agencies that receive certification requests must annually report to the Legislature the number of victims that requested certifications from the particular agency, the number of certifications signed, and the number of certifications denied. The certifications are for U and T Visas. 

I am requesting 
- The annual reports sent to the legislature as legally required since 2018. 
- Department U visa certification policy and protocols since 2024
- Bulletins, emails, memos, directives, or any communications from DHS and/or United States Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS) regarding SB674 and Form I-914s. Search January 2025 to today's date. 
- Any memos, bulletins, directives, or formal communications regarding U and T Visas. Search from 2020 to today's date. 

Thank you!

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation)

communications.subject: North Dakota Open Records Law Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the North Dakota Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

Lara Nochomovitz 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR185124 
Boston, Massachusetts 02115 

Re:  2025-HQFO-03921 

Dear Requester: 

This letter acknowledges receipt of your 4/20/2025, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to the Department of Homeland Security (DHS), for: 
1. Any and all files, policies, memos, reports, and/or other documents since January 1, 2020 containing the term "Naval Station Guantanamo Bay (JTF Camp Six and Migrant Ops Center Main A)" or "Guantanamo Bay". This request is limited to responsive records since 

2. A copy of the log of all Freedom of Information Act request made between 2020 and 2025 containing the term "Naval Station Guantanamo Bay (JTF Camp Six and Migrant Ops Center Main A)" or "Guantanamo Bay.".  This office received your request on 4/20/2025. 

As it pertains to item 1 ONLY, this will be under the purview of ICE. Please submit a request directly to their FOIA office: 
Freedom of Information Act Office 
500 12th Street, SW, Stop 5009 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5009 
Phone: 866-633-1182 | Fax: 202-732-4265 | E-mail: ice-foia@ice.dhs.gov 

Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request for item 2.  Consistent with 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, the Department processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt.  Although DHS’ goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period in certain circumstances pursuant to 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(c). 

Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS FOIA regulations as they apply to non-commercial requesters.  As a non-commercial requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free, as are the first two hours of search time, after which you will pay the per quarter-hour rate ($4.00 for clerical personnel, $7.00 for professional personnel, $10.25 for managerial personnel) of the searcher. We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00.  This office will contact you before accruing any further fees. 

We have queried the appropriate component(s) of DHS for responsive records.  If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability.  Please be assured that one of the analysts in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible.  We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request. 

Your request has been assigned reference number 2025-HQFO-03921.  Please refer to this identifier in any future correspondence. 

If you have any questions, or would like to discuss this matter, please feel free to contact this office at 1-866-431-0486 or 202-343-1743.

05/30/2025 

Lara Nochomovitz 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR185124 
Boston, Massachusetts 02115 

Re:  2025-HQFO-03921 

Dear Requester: 

This letter is the final response to your 4/20/2025 Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request addressed to the Department of Homeland Security (DHS).  You requested copies of all Freedom of Information Act request made between 2020 and 2025 containing the term "Naval Station Guantanamo Bay (JTF Camp Six and Migrant Ops Center Main A)" or "Guantanamo Bay.".  This office received your request on 4/20/2025. 

Information responsive to your request is accessible online at DHS Privacy FOIA Logs | Homeland Security. On or around July 31, 2025, the FOIA logs for Q1 of 2025 will be available. Pursuant to 5 U.S.C. § 552 (a)(1) and (a)(2), DHS need not make available under FOIA records that are publicly available. (https://www.dhs.gov/publication/dhs-privacy-foia-logs) 

If you deem this to be an adverse determination, you may exercise your appeal rights.  Should you wish to do so, you must send your appeal and a copy of this letter, within 90 days of the date of this letter, to:  Privacy Office, Attn: FOIA Appeals, U.S. Department of Homeland Security, 2707 Martin Luther King Jr. Avenue, SE, Mail Stop 0655, Washington, D.C. 20528-0655, following the procedures outlined in the DHS FOIA regulations at 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.5(e)(2).  Your envelope and letter should be marked “FOIA Appeal.”  Copies of the FOIA and DHS FOIA regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia. 

Provisions of FOIA allow DHS to charge for processing fees, up to $25, unless you seek a waiver of fees.  In this instance, because the cost is below the $25 minimum, there is no charge. 

If you need any further assistance or would like to discuss any aspect of your request, please contact the analyst below who processed your request and refer to 2025-HQFO-03921. You may send an e-mail to foia@hq.dhs.gov, call 202-343-1743 or toll free 1-866-431-0486, or you may contact our FOIA Public Liaison in the same manner.  Additionally, you have a right to right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at 202-741-5769.

title: John W. Gardner

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: John W. Gardner
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning, relating to, or generated as a result of investigation or inquiry of John William Gardner (October 8, 1912 - February 16, 2002). Proof of death is not required as his death was widely reported: https://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/18/us/john-w-gardner-89-founder-of-common-cause-and-adviser-to-presidents-dies.html

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies at FBI Headquarters. Please also conduct a search for records at the Alexandria Records Center. If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Galante

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1612529-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request

If your FOIPA Number is [1195846-0] please enter [1195846-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1195846-1] please enter [1195846-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000
Case Type:
FOIPA
Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)

The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.

You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system, and the FBI receives a voluminous amount of requests on a daily, weekly, monthly, and annual basis.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Our complex requests are further divided into small (51-250 pages), medium (251-500 pages), large (501-4,999), and extra-large (over 5,000 pages) sub-tracks.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  The more potentially responsive pages a request has, the more complex it becomes, greatly increasing the time required for processing. Generally, the larger the file, the longer it takes to process.

Currently, simple track cases average approximately 122 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Complex requests in the small processing track are currently averaging 360 days from the date of receipt for processing, those in the medium processing track are currently averaging 1,230 days, those in the large processing track are currently averaging approximately 2,010 days, and those in the extra-large track are averaging 2,370 days.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Oklahoma Open Records Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Oklahoma Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

communications.subject: RE: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Ohio Medical Board
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Anderson,

Thank you again for your exceptionally thorough and professional response to our public records request. Your office’s transparency and attention to detail — especially in providing internal memos, compliance statistics, and documents on the One-Bite and Confidential Monitoring Programs — stands in stark contrast to the approach taken by many other states. We’re sincerely grateful for your willingness to engage so substantively.

The internal memos you provided reflect a thoughtful, evolving understanding of physician impairment — particularly your recognition that models like One-Bite may discourage physicians from seeking help. The move toward a Confidential Monitoring Program with expanded eligibility, nuanced relapse handling, and clinical discretion is a promising step that other jurisdictions would do well to study.

As part of our ongoing national research initiative on PHP structures and board oversight, I would like to respectfully submit a brief follow-up request for materials that speak directly to program effectiveness and accountability — a key area where many states (even those with strong intentions) still lack meaningful insight:

1. Program Evaluations or Effectiveness Reviews
While the provided statistics are invaluable, we did not locate any:

Formal internal or external audits of OPHP program effectiveness.

Outcome tracking data (e.g., long-term return to practice, relapse rates, recidivism).

Physician feedback or satisfaction surveys regarding the program.

If any summaries, reports, evaluations, or even raw de-identified data exist, we would be very grateful for the opportunity to review them.

2. Appeal and Oversight Structures
Could you clarify:

Whether participants in the Confidential Monitoring Program have any avenues for appeal or recourse if they are found ineligible or removed from the program.

How OPHP determinations are reviewed, audited, or overseen, either by the Medical Board or a third-party body.

3. Contracts and Meeting Minutes
Lastly, if available, we respectfully request:

A copy of the contract, agreement, or MOU between OPHP and the State Medical Board of Ohio.

Any meeting minutes or internal policy discussions (from 2019–2024) where OPHP program performance, reforms, or challenges were reviewed.

We are not requesting names or identifying details and welcome redacted versions as needed.

Again, thank you for the exemplary transparency already shown. We’re grateful for your leadership and the Board’s evolving approach to protecting public safety while supporting physician wellness. Please don’t hesitate to reach out if any portion of this follow-up needs clarification.

Warm regards,

communications.subject: Response to Public Records Request
communications.communication:
Mr. Sinclair:

Your public records request submitted to the State Medical Board of Ohio was forwarded to me for review.  You requested the following regarding OhioPHP and the Board's Confidential Monitoring Program:


  1.  Program Evaluations or Effectiveness Reviews including formal internal or external audits of OPHP program effectiveness; outcome tracking data (e.g. long-term return to practice, relapse rates, recidivism); and physician feedback or satisfaction surveys regarding the program;
  2.  Appeal and Oversight Structures, including whether participants in the Confidential Monitoring Program have any avenues for appeal or recourse if they are found ineligible or removed from the program; and how OPHP determinations are reviewed, audited or overseen either by the Medical Board or a third-party body;
  3.  Contracts and Meeting Minutes, including a copy of the contract, agreement, or MOU between OPHP and the State Medical Board of Ohio and any meeting minutes or internal policy discussions from 2019 through 2024 where OPHP program performance, reforms or challenges were reviewed.
With respect to request number 1, attached please find the Special Program Report covering October 2023 through December 2024, for the first year of the Confidential Monitoring Program.  The Medical Board does not have any responsive documents regarding physician feedback or satisfaction surveys.

With respect to request number 2, the State Medical Board does not have any responsive documents regarding a participant's appeal of a decision to OhioPHP.  For individuals who are found ineligible for the Confidential Monitoring Program and referred to the State Medical Board, all formal disciplinary proceedings would be conducted in accordance with the Medical Board's laws and rules and Chapter 119 of the Ohio Revised Code regarding administrative appeals.  With respect to oversight of the Confidential Monitoring Program, Sections 4731.25 through 4731.255, Ohio Revised Code and rules in Chapter 4731-16, Ohio Administrative Code are applicable.  The statutes and rules may be accessed on the Medical Board's website at https://med.ohio.gov/laws-and-regulations

With respect to request number 3, attached please find the current contract between the State Medical Board of Ohio and OPHP.  With respect to minutes of the Board meetings, please note that the minutes are available on the Medical Board's website at https://med.ohio.gov/about-the-board/communications/board-meetings-and-minutes/board-meeting-agenda-minutes-landing

This completes your public records request in its entirety.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: USTDA historical reports
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Internal communications, including but not limited to emails, memos, and directives regarding any removal, modification, or restriction to public access of all available historical reports, dating back to 2020, that were previously housed online in the USTDA Library: https://www.ustda.gov/ustda-library.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Kelly Kauffman

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)

communications.subject: Maine Freedom of Access Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maine Freedom of Access Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by 1 M.R.S.A. § 408(6). The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

communications.subject: Maine Freedom of Access Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
The Maine Department of Corrections has received your request for information under the Maine Freedom of Access Act (FOAA).  Your request will be evaluated to determine if it comes within the FOAA, if it is clear as to what information you are requesting, and if nonconfidential records already exist that would fulfill all or part of your request.  If your request does not come within the FOAA, is not clear, or no records exist, you will be so notified.  If records exist, but they are confidential, you will be notified of the basis for that determination.  If nonconfidential records exist, you will be provided a good faith, nonbinding estimate of the time within which you will be provided the records, as well as an estimate of the costs that are allowed by the FOAA, if applicable.

V/r

Jenna Heald
Maine Department of Corrections
Policy & PowerDMS Assistant
FOAA Coordinator

I am asking for records related to the replacement, relocation, and repair of ALPR cameras. 

Please include copies of invoices related to the replacement, relocation, and repair of ALPR cameras and related accessories. Copies should be in .csv format if possible, otherwise related in digital form. 

Include locations of the reinstalled or fixed ALPRs. 

Please search 2019 to today's date.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Joey Scott

title: Child welfare predictive analytics systems

communications.subject: Arizona Public Records Law Request: Child welfare predictive analytics systems
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arizona Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

1) Contracts with any company, nonprofit, or other entity that currently provides software to the department that includes predictive analytics models for child welfare (i.e., models designed to identify home placement risk, abuse risk, human trafficking risk, etc.). This should include contracts for CCWIS or comparable systems that include predictive models as well as project descriptions for any models created in-house.

2) Data dictionaries for all child welfare predictive models used by the department, including those provided by outside entities as well as in-house models. Data dictionaries are  documents commonly created for predictive models and databases. They describe the categories of data that are inputs (age, gender, etc.) and outputs (risk level, etc.) of predictive models. They are equivalent to headers on a spreadsheet, and do not include actual data.

3) A list of all memorandums of understanding (MOUs) and/or data sharing agreements with state or local agencies for the provision of data that is incorporated into the department's child welfare predictive models. Should the department not maintain a list of these MOUs, I will accept copies of the MOUs themselves.

4) Any differential impact assessments, validation studies, or comparable documents that describe the accuracy of child welfare predictive models used by the department. This should include any documents that describe common measures of predictive accuracy, such as area under the curve (AUC).

5) All department policies, employee manuals, and guidelines describing how employees can and/or should use child welfare predictive models. 

6) All governance board, committee, or outside expert reviews assessing the efficacy of the department's proposed or current child welfare predictive models.

Should you have questions regarding any aspect of this request, please don't hesitate to contact me.

I ask that all fees be waived as I am a journalist and intend to use the requested records to publish articles in the public interest. In the event you choose to impose fees, I request a detailed breakdown of the fees, including the hourly wage of each employ involved and an explanation justifying the employee hours required to fulfill the request.

Should you choose to reject this request or redact portions of it, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to withhold each/any portions from public review.

I would prefer the request be filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you very much for your help, and I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Todd Feathers

communications.subject: RE: Arizona Public Records Law Request: Child welfare predictive analytics systems
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

I wanted to follow up on the following Arizona Public Records Law request, copied below, and originally submitted on April 30, 2021. Please let me know when I can expect to receive a response.  This communication was originally to DCSRecordsRequest@azdes.gov. Please see the following request. 
---
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arizona Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

1) Contracts with any company, nonprofit, or other entity that currently provides software to the department that includes predictive analytics models for child welfare (i.e., models designed to identify home placement risk, abuse risk, human trafficking risk, etc.). This should include contracts for CCWIS or comparable systems that include predictive models as well as project descriptions for any models created in-house.

2) Data dictionaries for all child welfare predictive models used by the department, including those provided by outside entities as well as in-house models. Data dictionaries are documents commonly created for predictive models and databases. They describe the categories of data that are inputs (age, gender, etc.) and outputs (risk level, etc.) of predictive models. They are equivalent to headers on a spreadsheet, and do not include actual data.

3) A list of all memorandums of understanding (MOUs) and/or data sharing agreements with state or local agencies for the provision of data that is incorporated into the department's child welfare predictive models. Should the department not maintain a list of these MOUs, I will accept copies of the MOUs themselves.

4) Any differential impact assessments, validation studies, or comparable documents that describe the accuracy of child welfare predictive models used by the department. This should include any documents that describe common measures of predictive accuracy, such as area under the curve (AUC).

5) All department policies, employee manuals, and guidelines describing how employees can and/or should use child welfare predictive models.

6) All governance board, committee, or outside expert reviews assessing the efficacy of the department's proposed or current child welfare predictive models.

Should you have questions regarding any aspect of this request, please don't hesitate to contact me.

I ask that all fees be waived as I am a journalist and intend to use the requested records to publish articles in the public interest. In the event you choose to impose fees, I request a detailed breakdown of the fees, including the hourly wage of each employ involved and an explanation justifying the employee hours required to fulfill the request.

Should you choose to reject this request or redact portions of it, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to withhold each/any portions from public review.

I would prefer the request be filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you very much for your help, and I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Todd Feathers

communications.subject: Thank you! Your request has been received
communications.communication:
This is to acknowledge that the Department of Child Safety (DCS) is in
receipt of your recent correspondence. Your information will be provided to
the appropriate program for review and a response will be provided to you in
a timely manner.

If you suspect that a child is being abused and/or neglected call the Arizona
Child Abuse Hotline at 1-888-SOS-CHILD (1-888-767-2445).


    ==Contact Information==

title: Larry Flynt (FBI)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Larry Flynt (FBI)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of all documents or FBI files pertaining, or mentioning to Larry Flynt, a pornographic magazine entrepreneur most notable for his production of "Hustler" Magazine. According to news reports, Mr. Flynt died in February of 2021 (https://apnews.com/article/larry-flynt-dead-0ae38f6dca115aed20cb88d5fc547e99) and therefore neither FOIA's b6 exemption nor the Privacy Act relate to him. See also the supporting documentation. His DOB was November 1, 1942 and he died on February 10, 2021.

The request is being made my a member of the news media and I plan to use the original documents and my editorial skills to turn the raw materials into a distinct work. I further intend to distribute my work and the documents to a general audience.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emily Crose

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1501812-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on "Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request" on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI's FOIPA Program is searching the FBI's indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 152 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 922 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 1,964 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,360 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive

title: Water Asset Management funds correspondence

communications.subject: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. All email correspondence, with attachments, mentioning "Water Property Investors," "Water Property Investor II," or "Water Property Investor III." 

2. Pitch decks, prospectuses, or any other materials provided to NMERB by the the above funds for consideration of potential investments.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Julia Rock

communications.subject: Fw: [EXTERNAL] New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Records Requestor:


Your request for information from the New Mexico Educational Retirement Board was forwarded to me. In accordance with the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act (IPRA), “a written request shall provide the name, address and telephone number of the person seeking access to the records and shall identify the records sought with reasonable particularity.” Section 14-2-8(C) NMSA 1978.


If you will provide me with your name and mailing address, we can begin the process of allowing inspection of the relevant records.


The Inspection of Public Records Act can be found at 14-2-1 through 14-2-12 NMSA 1978.


Thank you.


Amanda Olsen



Amanda Olsen, Paralegal
NM Educational Retirement Board
PO Box 26129

communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Scroggins and Ms. Olsen,

Thanks for the update. Can you provide any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request, or the estimated delivery date? Please feel free to give me a call at 781-962-8816 if it'd be helpful to discuss the scope of the materials we're requesting.

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

[cid:image001.png@01D9C623.0D3F7D80]

I'm following up on the following New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act request, copied below, and originally submitted on June 5, 2023. You had previously indicated that it would be completed on Nov. 6, 2023. I wanted to check on the status of my request, and to see if there was a new estimated completion date.

Thanks for your help, and let me know if further clarification is needed.

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL] RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Please see the attached concerning your request to inspect public records with the New Mexico Educational Retirement Board.

Thank you.

Amanda Olsen

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Hello Ms. Garcia,

Thank you for the update. Given that it's now been five months since we filed the initial request, are you able to provide an update as to whether you've identified the responsive documents, or what the source of the delay is?

Thank you,

Rebecca

communications.subject: ATTORNEY CLIENT PRIVILEGED - RE: [EXTERNAL] RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

Thank you for your inquiry and please accept our apologies for the delay.

As Mr. Scroggins noted in his August 3, 2023 email regarding our projected response, we always try to be prompt.  But as you might guess, the request references a large number of records.  As he said, we must thoroughly review all records to identify and obtain the responsive documents from both external and internal sources.  It is a complex and time-consuming process.

I am confident that we will have documents ready to provide on or before the December 6th, 2023, date noted in our recent communication.

Thank you for your continued patience!
Regards,
Renee



[cid:image002.png@01DA121F.C2136CB0]

files.title: image002
files.source: New Mexico Educational Retirement Board, New Mexico

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Hi,

Thanks so much for your help with this request! I really appreciate it.

Sincerely,
Julia Rock

communications.subject: Re: Request for Inspection of Records
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns:

As discussed in our letter of December 6, 2023, we are providing the records we currently have available in response to your June 16, 2023, request.  They are located at the website below:

MuckRock - Julia Rock<https://nmgov-my.sharepoint.com/:f:/r/personal/renee_garcia_erb_nm_gov/Documents/MuckRock%20-%20Julia%20Rock?csf=1&web=1&e=4gwfSH>

As also discussed, we will require additional time to provide the remainder of the records.  We plan to provide additional documents on or before February 1, 2024.  Thank you again for your continued patience regarding this matter.
Regards,
Renee



[cid:image001.png@01DA29F0.5D899B00]

communications.communication:
Hello Renee,

Thank you for your continued partnership on this request. Please know that we are unable to access the SharePoint link you had provided. Our email address is not showing as associated with the link: 147140-15493170@requests.muckrock.com.

Please advise at your earliest convenience.

Thank You,

MuckRock Staff

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Hello Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

We apologize for the error you received while trying to access the records. We will be using another method for delivery. Attached are the instructions that you will need to connect to the ERB SFTP server.  I will send you the credentials in a secure email to follow this.

As also discussed, we will require additional time to provide the remainder of the records. We plan to provide additional documents on or before February 1, 2024. Thank you again for your continued patience regarding this matter.
Regards,
Renee



[cid:image001.png@01DA2C20.B2CBD790]

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Correction)

communications.subject: Arkansas Freedom of Information Act Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Correction)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arkansas Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Sonny Albarado, a citizen of Arkansas, in coordination with Andrew Ma.
