title: Maryland Board of Medicine

communications.subject: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Maryland Board of Medicine
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maryland Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. All physician disciplinary actions from 2019-2024 related to:
   - Mental health conditions
   - Substance use
   - Behavioral health issues

2. Board policies regarding physician health programs

3. Statistics on:
   - Self-reported vs. discovered cases
   - Return to practice rates
   - Appeal outcomes
   
4. Any studies or reports on physician mental health programs

5. Details about Maryland Professional Rehabilitation Program (MPRP):
   - Relationship/agreements with medical board
   - Confidentiality policies
   - Rate of board reporting
   - Statistics on physician outcomes
   - Any formal or informal agreements between MPRP and board

6. Any evaluations or audits of MPRP effectiveness

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Vig Sinclair

communications.subject: RE: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Maryland Board of Medicine
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Anderson:
Thank you for your response dated March 4, 2025, to our Public Information Act request concerning physician disciplinary actions, health programs, and the Maryland Professional Rehabilitation Program (MPRP).
I am writing on behalf of a research organization, which is conducting nationwide research on physician health programs and rehabilitation systems. This research will culminate in a published book documenting how each state handles these critical matters of public health and professional oversight.
While I appreciate your prompt response, I have significant concerns about the transparency limitations revealed in your letter:

Disciplinary Action Data: Although you indicate the Board only tracks complaints by disciplinary grounds, this approach creates a concerning gap in understanding how mental health and substance abuse issues affect physician practice. Even if the data isn't categorized exactly as requested, would it be possible to provide the raw disciplinary data you do have? Our research team has expertise in analyzing such information to identify relevant patterns.
Absence of Information: It is surprising that the Board maintains "no information responsive" to four of our six requests, particularly regarding physician health programs. This suggests a potential gap in oversight that may be worth addressing at the policy level.
MPRP Information: Rather than simply redirecting us to the Office of Contract Management and Procurement (OCMP), would your office be willing to facilitate this connection or provide a specific contact person? As a state-sponsored program affecting physician licensure, greater coordination between agencies would benefit the public interest.

Our book will document how each state responds to these requests, highlighting both exemplary transparency practices and areas for improvement. 
We would welcome the opportunity to revise our request in a way that might yield more substantive information, or to discuss alternative approaches to obtaining this important data. Public understanding of physician health programs serves both the medical community and patient safety.
Please feel free to contact me directly at [phone/email] if you would like to discuss how we might work together more productively on this matter.
Sincerely,

communications.subject: Re: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Maryland Board of Medicine
communications.communication:
Good day Mr. Sinclair,

The MD Board of Physicians (the Board) received a Public Information Act
request from you dated February 13, 2025, and responded to your request on
March 4, 2025, which you acknowledged receiving in your email dated April
18, 2025.

To reiterate, in the PIA response letter to you dated March 4, 2025, the
Board did not provide any records responsive to your request.  In your
follow-up email, you ask if it's possible to receive our complaint data in
a "raw" format that your research team would then analyze to identify
relevant patterns.  Under Maryland PIA laws, the Board's investigative
records, which include complaints, are confidential and prohibited from
public inspection.  Disclosure of these records is prohibited under GP §
4-301(a)(2)(i).  This provision of the PIA prohibits disclosure of a record
when disclosure is contrary to a state statute.  In this case, section
§14-411(b) of the Maryland Medical Practice Act expressly prohibits the
Board, a disciplinary panel, or any of its investigatory bodies from
disclosing any information contained in a record. Furthermore, all
disclosable, public information regarding disciplinary actions against
licensees is available for viewing on the Board's website
<https://www.mbp.state.md.us/sanctions.aspx>.

For items two through six, you requested information on statistical data,
studies, policies, audits, reports on physician health programs, and
specifically the Maryland Physician Health Program (previously referred to
as MPRP).  Again, the Board has no information responsive to your request.
The MPHP
<https://www.mbp.state.md.us/resource_information/res_pro/resource_Practitioner_rehab_volunteer.aspx>
is a voluntary, independent program not affiliated with the Board, as
stated on our website. You were also directed to the resources to contact
regarding your request for details on the relationship/agreement between
MPHP and the Board.

*Pursuant to GP §4-362, you are entitled to seek judicial review of this
decision.  You may also refer any concerns about this decision to the
Public Access Ombudsman in accordance with GP § 4-1B-01 et seq.*

Sincerely,

Rhonda Anderson

communications.subject: RE: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Maryland Board of Medicine
communications.communication:
To Rhonda Anderson and the Maryland Board of Physicians:
Re: Appeal of PIA Response dated May 7, 2025
I am writing to challenge the Board's continued refusal to provide meaningful information in response to my Public Information Act request dated February 13, 2025.
Your latest response mischaracterizes both my request and Maryland law in several critical ways:

False Claim of Independence: You assert that the Maryland Physician Health Program (MPHP) is "a voluntary, independent program not affiliated with the Board." This claim is demonstrably false. The MPHP is explicitly referenced in COMAR 10.32.22 as a "rehabilitation program" approved by the Board. By law, the Board must maintain documentation of this approval relationship. Your denial of any responsive records suggests either regulatory negligence or deliberate concealment.
Misapplication of Confidentiality Provisions: While MD Code, Gen. Prov. § 4-301(a)(2)(i) and Medical Practice Act § 14-411(b) protect individual case information, they do NOT exempt aggregate statistical data, policies, or contractual agreements from disclosure. Your blanket citation of these provisions without distinguishing between protected individual records and disclosable administrative documents reflects a concerning overreach of confidentiality provisions.
Failure to Segregate Disclosable Information: Maryland PIA requires agencies to separate exempt from non-exempt material rather than withholding entire categories of documents. Your failure to identify which specific records exist but are being withheld, versus which genuinely don't exist, violates both the letter and spirit of the PIA.
Public Interest Considerations: The Maryland Court of Appeals has consistently held that PIA exemptions must be "narrowly construed" in favor of disclosure, particularly when matters of public health and governance are concerned. The Board's relationship with MPHP directly impacts both physician welfare and patient safety - core public interests that outweigh generalized confidentiality claims.
Comparison to Other State Practices: The North Carolina Medical Board, responding to an identical request, provided comprehensive documentation of its relationship with its physician health program, statistical reports, and procedural documents - all without compromising individual confidentiality. Maryland's refusal to provide even basic policy documentation stands in stark contrast to this model of transparency.

Your suggestion that my only recourse is judicial review or an Ombudsman complaint reflects an unfortunate unwillingness to engage substantively with legitimate public interest concerns.
I respectfully request that the Board:

Immediately provide all contracts, MOUs, or agreements between the Board and MPHP
Release redacted versions of policies or procedural documents governing referrals to MPHP
Produce aggregate statistical information that does not identify individual physicians
Provide any audits or evaluations of the MPHP program's effectiveness

If the Board maintains its refusal to provide any responsive documents whatsoever, I request written certification from the Executive Director personally attesting that the Board maintains absolutely no documentation of its relationship with a program explicitly referenced in its own regulations.
I look forward to your response within 10 business days. Please be advised that I am simultaneously filing a complaint with the Public Access Ombudsman and exploring options for judicial review as suggested in your communication.
Sincerely,
Vig Sinclair
cc: Maryland Public Access Ombudsman
Maryland Attorney General's Office, Open Government Division

All department policy and guidance documents regarding transgender inmates, including but not limited to gender-affirming medical care, housing and treatment by staff. Sincerely,

Ileana Garnand

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Chief FOIA officer's recent email (Federal Bureau of Investigation)
communications.communication:
Dear Federal Bureau of Investigation,

On behalf of myself and Fiat Fiendum, I hereby request the following records:

1. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email inbox or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
2. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email spam folder or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
3. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's sent email folder or equivalent which was sent nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
4. The total full-time equivalent count of people who work for your FOIA office as of October 19, 2024.

This request is expressly limited to Federal Bureau of Investigation's own FOIA office. Please do not refer it to any other agency or division. This request is expressly not a Privacy Act request, and no PA waiver will be provided.

Please provide the email records in EML, Maildir, MBOX, MIX, MSG, or PST format only — not PDF, Word, image, etc — including all metadata (e.g. full email headers as received/sent) and attachments, without alteration other than narrowly tailored electronic redaction of specifically claimed exemptions that do not affect any part of non exempt information (and, in particular, without rasterization).

Please provide the fourth record as a statement in your response letter, or at your option, as the most readily available record, in original electronic format as currently stored on your computer systems, which includes that information.

Please provide all records either as individual files, or as an unencrypted ZIP file, uploaded to MuckRock. Do not apply any encryption, DRM, or other restriction.

I request fee waiver, because
* Fiat Fiendum is a 501(c)(3) non-profit;
* this request is for public interest, non-commercial purposes;
* these records would give a snapshot of insight into the everyday processes of FOIA offices; and
* these records are being requested in order to conduct a government-wide audit of agencies' FOIA compliance.

In the event that you deny fee waiver, please process this request as-is, because I will not agree to any fees.

Please be sure to provide:
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(II) FOIA Public Liaison information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(aa) appeal information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(bb) OGIS information
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(A) tracking number
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(B)(ii) completion ETA

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
Sai
President, Fiat Fiendum, Inc.

P.S. Sai is my full legal name.

title: Glenn R. Miles FBI Files

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Glenn R. Miles FBI Files
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I request any FBI records pertaining to Glenn R. Miles, who was killed in the line of duty as a Customs Agent for the U.S. Treasury Department in Arizona on February 21, 1986. This request includes, but is not limited to any FBI lab analysis of Agent Miles' handheld audio recorder, or references to its contents, as well as any 302s or field reports regarding Agent Miles' potential interactions with the alleged drug traffickers who were reportedly involved in his murder. Finally, this request includes any records sent or received by FBI to William Laverty, U.S. Customs Attache at the U.S. Embassy in Mexico City regarding the July 1986 arrest of five Mexican nationals in Hermosillo, Sonora, Mexico who were alleged to have been involved with the slaying.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Free

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)

communications.subject: South Carolina Public Records Law Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the South Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

title: RNL contracts and reports

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: RNL contracts and reports
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) All documentation since Jan. 1, 2017 of the university's contracts with Ruffalo, Noel, Levitz (RNL) for the firm's Demand Builder, Applicant Cultivator, ForecastPlus, and/or Student Search Predictive  Analytics services. Specifically, this should include contracts, statements of work, successful RFP response packages, sole source agreements, and data privacy agreements. 

2) All model workbooks for the university's Demand Builder, Applicant Cultivator, ForecastPlus, and/or Student Search Predictive Analytics models. These workbooks, which RNL provides in Excel or other spreadsheet format, contain the model(s)' glossary of variables, market summaries,  and model scores and results,  among other information. If it would aid in your search, I can provide an example of an RNL model workbook.

3) All plans and reports prepared by the university enrollment staff or RNL since Jan. 1, 2017 regarding the university's use of the Demand Builder, Applicant Cultivator, ForecastPlus, and/or Student Search Predictive Analytics model results.  This includes, but is not limited to, plans and reports describing the university's use of model scores to inform student list purchases, targeted communication campaigns, and/or recruiting trips.

4) All end-year conversion reports prepared for the university by RNL since Jan. 1, 2017. If it would aid in your search, I can provide an example of an RNL end-year conversion report.

5) All prospect analysis reports prepared for the university by RNL since Jan. 1, 2017. If it would aid in your search, I can provide an example of an RNL end-year conversion report.

I ask that all fees be waived as intend to use the requested records to further public understanding of public agencies.

Should you choose to reject this request or redact portions of responsive documents, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to withhold each/any portions from public review.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Todd Feathers

The closure reason supplied was: Dear Requester, Records responsive to your Public Records Request are available at https://wsu.nextrequest.com.  Also available is an index identifying information that has been redacted and the legal reasons for each such action in accordance with the Public Records Act (RCW 42.56). This is the final response from Washington State University regarding your request. Your request is now closed, and any subsequent request for the same material will be processed as a separate, new request. Washington State University does not intend to further address the request, and the Public Records Act’s one-year statute of limitations to seek judicial review has started to run as of the date of this email. Please contact us within 30 days if you have any questions. Please contact this office if you have any questions. Public Records Office Washington State University ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at Washington State University.

Technical support: See our help page

title: Refinery29 Media Request For Title IX Complaint Records

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Refinery29 Media Request For Title IX Complaint Records
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any and all Title IX complaints involving The University of Nebraska Lincoln within the past 5 years.

In order to help to determine my status to assess fees, you should know that I am a representative of the news media affiliated with Refinery29 and Vice Media Group, and this request is made as part of news gathering and not for a commercial use.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Molly Longman

title: Town of Fairfax Homeless Management Policies

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Town of Fairfax Homeless Management Policies
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All policies and procedures that relate to "homelessness" in the Town of Fairfax.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robbie Powelson

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request - Jeffrey Alan Lincoln
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to formally request access to video footage from a police intervention, specifically from the body camera worn by the officer(s) and the dashcam of the police vehicles involved. Article:
https://cbsaustin.com/news/nation-world/jeffrey-alan-lincoln-florida-dui-driving-intoxicated-repeat-offender-criminal-history-jail-told-charges-arrests-carried-car-deputy-vodka-bottle-traffic-stop-pickup-truck-drinking-lanes-yelling-marion-brevard-broward-county-breath-test-sheriff-office

Exact date of incident: June 30, 2024
Names of parties involved: Jeffrey Alan Lincoln


I intend to use this footage solely for educational purposes to promote a better understanding of law enforcement procedures and the application of the law.

I understand that there may be associated costs for providing this footage, and I am more than willing to cover any fees incurred. Please inform me about the necessary procedures and the costs involved.

Thank you in advance for your assistance. I trust that this footage will be invaluable for my educational efforts, and I greatly appreciate your cooperation.


Best regards,
George Smith

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

George Smith

title: Surfline (Middletown Town Clerk)

communications.subject: Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act Request: Surfline (Middletown Town Clerk)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

The company Surfline has been advertising persistent monitoring of beaches in your town: www.surfline.com. Therefore, I request the following:

1) All instructional materials, presentations and presentation materials (including recorded video and audio, PowerPoint files, prepared remarks, and slides formats), and other guidance on the use of Surfline or Surfzone.ai. This includes A) any notes taken during meetings that discussed the use of Surfline, B) any explanations (whether internally or externally generated) of how Surfline works, and C) any other document that has been used to help explain the use of Surfline, including internal documentation, public relations materials, and executive summaries.

2) A copy of any privacy impact assessments, use policies, standard operating procedures, data retention policies, legal opinions, warranties, non-disclosure agreements, contracts, liability waivers, insurance agreements, Requests for Proposals, Responses to Requests for Proposal, Memorandums of Understanding, Letters of Interest, usage policies, or informal agreements between the department and Surfline, Surfzone.ai, or Wavetrak.

3) A copy of any funding opportunity announcements, grant applications and grantor status/progress reports, reports to legislative bodies, annual reports that mention Surfline, Surfzone.ai, or Wavetrak, as well as audit records, including but not limited to security audits of the software, misuse reports, and reports to oversight bodies.

4) Any digital communications including but not limited to emails and text messages) as well as documents, (including but not limited to PDF, word processing, excel, and slide documents) that mention Surfline, Surfzone.ai, or Wavetrak.

5) Any case reports in which Surfline was used.

6) Any digital communications (including but not limited to emails and text messages) with Surfline, Surfzone.ai, or Wavetrak representatives.

The documents will be used in the course of reporting for 404 Media, an independent tech journalism website (www.404media.co)

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jason Koebler

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Request: Operation Stonegarden
communications.communication:
Good Afternoon,

Regarding your FOIA request # 2017-FEFO-02310, the request is still out for a search.  Please note that our office and the program office were we sent the records search are both experiencing delays due to staff deployments in response to Hurricanes Harvey, Irma, Maria, Nate and the California wildfires.  We will make every attempt to process and complete your request as soon as possible.  Thank you for your understanding.
Regards,

The FEMA Disclosure Branch

communications.subject: FEMA FOIA 2017-FEFO-02310 - Need More Information - Reply by Dec. 12
communications.communication:
Good Morning Ms. Raih: 
This correspondence is in regards to FEMA FOIA case number 
# 2017-FEFO-02310.   A copy of yourrequest is attached. 
The search produced records totaling several thousands ofpages that may be responsive to the request.  Given the sheer size and the fact that pages may need to beconsulted with other agencies who have equity in them, this may take many monthsto process. 
At this point, would youlike to narrow the scope of your request to only include a particular fiscalyear, or perhaps a short list of locations, that most interest you?  Yourequested the fiscal years and locations below.  Any narrowing of the request would help us to get meaningful records to you in a shorter amount of time. 
FY 13 
FY 14 
FY 15 
FY 16 
Location: all states and territories 
Your case has been placed on a brief hold. Please respond by December 12. Thankyou.
Regards, 
Kevin Hill

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: City of Novato Communications
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All communications between Kate Gauntlett and Heather Abrams between January 1st 2025 to April 22nd 2025

All communications between Lt. Alan Bates and Officer Thomas Lyons between January 1st 2025 to April 22nd 2025

All communications between Lt. Alan Bates and Capt. Jim Correa and Jim Naugle between January 1st 2025 to April 22nd 2025

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robbie Powelson

communications.subject: City Records Request :: N000380-042225
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
RE: City Records Request of April 22, 2025, Reference # N000380-042225 Dear Robbie Powelson, This is in response to your public records request received on April 22, 2025 and follows my message of May 1, 2025.. Your request asked for: All communications between Kate Gauntlett and Heather Abrams between January 1st 2025 to April 22nd 2025 

All communications between Lt. Alan Bates and Officer Thomas Lyons between January 1st 2025 to April 22nd 2025 

All communications between Lt. Alan Bates and Capt. Jim Correa and Jim Naugle between January 1st 2025 to April 22nd 2025 
The City has completed a reasonable search of its records and determined there are responsive documents as well as certain records and/or portions thereof which have been determined to be exempt from disclosure and will therefore not be disclosed pursuant to the statutory exemptions noted below: • Deliberative Process Privilege – Government Code section 7922.000; Times Mirror Co. v. Superior Court (1991) 53 Cal.3d 1325; California First Amendment Coalition v. Superior Court (1998) 67 Cal.App.4th 159 – The public interest in nondisclosure clearly outweighs the public interest in disclosure of records revealing the deliberations of agency officials used to reach a decision. 
• Preliminary Drafts and Similar Materials – Government Code section 7927.500 – Any preliminary drafts, notes, or interagency or intra-agency memoranda that are not retained by a public agency in the ordinary course of business are exempt from disclosure. 
• Personally Identifying Information – Government Code section 7922.000; American Civil Liberties Union Foundation v. Superior Court (2017) 221 Cal.Rptr.3d 832 – The public interest in nondisclosure clearly outweighs the public interest in disclosure of information that infringes upon privacy rights. 

• Official Information Privilege – Government Code section 7927.705, Evidence Code sections 1040 – Information acquired in confidence by a public employee in the course of his or her duty and not open, or officially disclosed, to the public prior to the time the claim of privilege is made. 

• Records Related to Law Enforcement or Security – Government Code section 7923.600 – Records of complaints to, or investigations conducted by, or records of intelligence information or security procedures of … any state or local police agency, or any investigatory or security files compiled by any other state or local police agency, or any investigatory or security files compiled by any other state or local agency for correctional, law enforcement, or licensing purposes. 

• Public interest balancing test - Government Code section 7922.000 – The public interest in nondisclosure clearly outweighs the public interest in disclosure. 
Please log in to the Public Records Center at the following link to retrieve the responsive records: City Records Request - N000380-042225  Please be advised the City will not allow inspection or copying of any privileged documents. While we will try to remove all privileged documents, the inadvertent inclusion of any privileged documents does not constitute a waiver and we ask you to notify us of any privileged material that is inadvertently provided. Also be advised the City is not required to produce documents that are exempt from disclosure under the California Public Records Act, records destroyed in accordance with Government Code section 34090 and the City’s records retention policy, or records that include such information that the public interest served by not disclosing the records clearly outweighs the public interest served by the disclosure of the records. 

Under Government Code section 7922.600, please let me know if you would like to discuss your request further or if I can assist you in clarifying the request, identifying records responsive to the request, or requesting additional records. 
Kindest regards, Laura McDowall 
City Clerk

title: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)

communications.subject: Iowa Open Records Law Request: Request for Correctional Mental Health Staff Directory and Contact Information (Department of Corrections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Iowa Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting a list of currently employed mental health professionals within your state's Department of Corrections or its subsidiary agencies, as well as their contact information.

Specifically, I am requesting:

- Full names
- Job titles
- Assigned correctional facility
- Government-issued email addresses
- Government-issued phone numbers (direct desk numbers if available, otherwise department phone numbers with or without extensions)
- Department/division (e.g. Behavioral Health, Mental Health Services)

This request applies to the following roles: rehabilitative program coordinators, licensed psychologists, psychiatrists, clinical social workers, and other licensed mental health professionals serving incarcerated populations in state-operated facilities.

If available, I request this information be provided in a machine-readable format such as CSV or Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Andrew Ma

communications.communication:
State of Iowa ************************************************************************ A document has been released for record request #25-1850 along with the following message: Thank you for your recent request (Request 25-1850). The Iowa Department of Corrections (DOC) charges for open record requests. Our office provides 30 minutes of staff review time without charge. Beyond that, our office charges based on the hourly wage of the staff member(s) handling the request. Accordingly, this request will take 4 hours of staff time with the first 30 minutes at no charge. Please review the attached charge form to determine if you would like to proceed with the request. communications.subject: RE: Iowa Open Records Law Request #25-1850
communications.communication:
Hi Jen,

Thank you for your response and for providing the fee estimate for Request 25-1850.

I’d like to respectfully amend the scope of the request, as our organization is a small nonprofit working to offer free, trauma-informed mindfulness and meditation programs to support the mental health of incarcerated individuals. Unfortunately, we do not currently have funding to cover the cost of the full record request.

Instead, I’d be very grateful if you could provide the name, title, work email, and phone number of  supervisory-level staff at the Iowa Department of Corrections who are responsible for overseeing or coordinating mental health services or programming within state correctional facilities.

I understand this may fall outside of a formal records search and hope this more limited request is feasible without significant cost. Any partial guidance or contact information you’re able to share would be sincerely appreciated.

Thank you again for your time and support.

Warm regards,
Andrew Ma

title: City of Novato 647 PC Inquiry

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: City of Novato 647 PC Inquiry
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All citations, tickets, reports, collated data etc that indicate the number and location of citations/arrests made under PC 647(e) and Novato Municipal Code 14-20

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robbie Powelson
